2.2. QFD method
Whenever considering any real-life decision-making pro­
blem, it is essential to consider customer requirements. 
The QFD method was developed to consider challenges 
associating with design, quality, and increment the chances 
of a study to cope with customer satisfaction (Sullivan 1986; 
Akao 1990). QFD makes use of a matrix known as House of 
Quality (HOQ) to relate Customer Needs/Requirements 
(CRs) and Design-associated Requirements (DRs) via engi­
neering characteristics (Onar et al. 2016). During its con­
struction, the HOQ considers the matrix showing how the 
DRs and CRs are related, the corresponding weights mark­
ing the importance of each CR and the matrix of correlation 
for the DRs (Sullivan 1986; Akao 1990; Onar et al. 2016; 
Prasad 1998). Elements of an arbitrary HOQ structure can 
be discussed as below:
CR: Often denoted as customer needs, attributes, or 
demanded quality, the foundation step of a HOQ is to identify, 
clarify and find out the customer needs (Onar et al. 2016). CRs 
represent the customer’s say or the customer’s viewpoint 
towards the selection of a product.
