I. INTRODUCTION
T
RANSPORATION electrification aids in reduced carbon
emissions. With the technological advancement and gov-
ernment incentives, the EVs ownership has increased [1].
Among the challenges in the large-scale EVs deployment,
inadequate charging infrastructure is a critical aspect that
needs to be addressed [2]. The charging infrastructure for
large-scale EV adoption can be categorized based on desti-
nation and urgent charging [2]. In destination charging, slow
chargers in parking lots primarily cater to the charging needs
in urban areas. In urgent charging, fast charging stations gen-
erally satisfy the EV charging requirements on the intra-city
corridors. The intra-city corridors are considered to connect
multiple suburbs in a metropolitan city. Planning of both
charging facilities is important [2]. However, more attention
is required on optimal planning of fast charging stations for
long distance trips to address the range anxiety among EV
owners [3].
The approaches for planning of fast EV charging stations
can be classified as 1) transportation, 2) electrical, and 3) mul-
tidisciplinary approaches. In the first approach, strategies for
placement of gasoline stations are redeveloped for EV charg-
ing stations, which are based on the nodal demand or traffic
flow [3], [4], [5], [6]. The charging stations deployed in [7]
do not consider the topology and requirements of EPDN.
The electrical approach aims to minimize the investment
cost of charging stations and grid upgrades, keeping in view
only the security and economic aspects of the EPDN [8].
In the multidisciplinary approach, the EV charging stations are
planned considering the perspectives of both the transportation
network and EPDN [9]. In the conventional multidisciplinary
approach [10], [11], two-step sequential planning is done,
where EV charging stations are placed first, followed by
the planning of EPDN. This may lead to high investment
cost due to sub-optimal utilization of charging station and
EPDN infrastructures. The research work in [12] performs the
resilience enhancement of a coupled urban transportation and
EPDN by line hardening and DG placement strategies while
considering the traffic light outages.
A multi-objective integrated planning for optimal sizing and
placement of fast charging stations is done in [13] based on
the distance between the transportation nodes while not mod-
ifying the EPDN parameters. A bi-level approach is presented
in [14] for the location and sizing of charging stations in the
coupled networks. The integrated planning of charging stations
in [13], [14], [15], [16], and [17] for urban areas does not
consider the driving range constraints of EVs. Furthermore,
the authors in [9], [17], [18], and [19] consider a few auxiliary
transportation charging station nodes, which are uncoupled
with the EPDN. Hence, exact coupling between EPDN and
transportation network is absent, which may not reflect the
actual impact of EV charging on EPDN, affecting the planning
of charging infrastructure. A coordinated planning approach
for EV charging stations is presented in [20] to evaluate the
expansion strategies for both transportation and the EPDNs.
An agent-based approach solves the siting challenge of EV
charging stations in [21]. Optimal sizing of renewable sources
and battery storage are determined in [22] for stand-alone
charging stations. However, the analysis in [21] and [22] does
not explicitly consider the impacts on the associated EPDN.
The capacity planning of charging stations powered by solar
panels and energy storage systems to minimize the investment
cost is presented in [23]. Expansion planning of EPDN and
transportation network is proposed in [24] without considering
the EV charging requirements. Further, the work in [24] has an
impractical assumption that all nodes in EPDN have the same
time-invariant non-EV demand. Table I summarizes the key
aspects missing in literature on planning of fast EV charging
stations.
It can be noted from Table I that the previous works
on planning of fast EV charging stations do not consider
several practical aspects associated with both the transportation
network and EPDN. The charging stations couple both, the
transportation and EPDNs, and hence, their location and
sizing affect the EV driving behavior and EPDN. However,
one to one coupling between nodes of the transportation
network and EPDN is missing, such as in [9], [14], [17],
[18], and [19]. Hence, the first contribution of this paper is
the optimal planning of fast EV charging stations in a fully
coupled transportation network and EPDN. To the best of the
authors’ knowledge, this work is unique in that it performs a
distance-based mapping between all transportation and EPDN
nodes for observing the impact of EV charging on EPDN.
Further, a major limitation in the previous works, such as
in [13], [15], [16], and [17], is the assumption of placing at
least one charging station in a path, which will fully capture
the traffic flow. This is not true as the EVs’ driving range
constraints are ignored or relaxed [13], [15], [16], [17], [20]
which include: a) determining whether the initial SOC of
EV battery meets the driving range required to reach the
charging station, and b) assess the SOCs of individual EVs
upon arrival and meet their charging requirements, i.e., their
driving range required to reach the destination and while
leaving the destination. It is challenging to satisfy both the
constraints, i.e., driving range and EPDN constraints simul-
taneously. However, the driving range constraints’ must be
