SUMMARY OF A FEW RELATED WORKS ON PLACEMENT AND SIZING OF FAST EV CHARGING STATIONS
satisfied along with the consideration of EPDN constraints,
since, it affects the EPDN. Thus, the second contribution of
this paper is that it considers all the above mentioned driving
range constraints while considering the EPDN constraints and
maximizing traffic flow.
The majority of previous works, such as [7], [9], [13], [14],
[15], [18], and [22] assume the EV charging demand to follow
the Poisson distribution [25]. In practise, the EV charging
demand is determined by traffic flow, which is significantly
influenced by the day type and weather. Therefore, the assump-
tion of EV charging demand to follow Poisson distribution is
impractical for the optimal planning of charging infrastructure.
Forecasting the EV charging demand is the foundation for
analyzing the impact of charging on EPDN and travel patterns
in the transportation network. Hence, an added feature of
this paper is to forecast the traffic flow using the RF tech-
nique while considering the key attributes of day type, hourly
weather, and hourly traffic flow. Additionally, the input data is
preprocessed using the Isolation Forest Method (IFM) [26]
for accurate forecasts. This improves the planning of fast
EV charging stations as the charging demand is determined
from the traffic flow forecast and suitable Probability Density
functions (PDFs) for the EV mobility parameters.
The existing literature on planning and operation of the
charging infrastructure designs multi-objective problem for-
mulation and utilize advanced meta-heuristic optimization
techniques, as discussed in [4], [5], [8], [11], [15], [16], and
[17]. For illustration, the paper [4] focuses on the optimal
placement of centralized charging stations using Binary Parti-
cle Swarm Optimization (BPSO). Further, the multi-objective
formulations in [11], [15], [16], and [17] are carried out for
optimal planning of EV charging stations and solved using
PSO, Genetic Algorithm (GA) [11], [17], and other evolution-
ary techniques [15], [16]. Similarly, the optimal placement
and sizing of distributed resources comprising of multiple
objectives and cosntraints in an EPDN is carried out using PSO
algorithm [27], [28]. PSO and its variants are mostly utilized
in EPDN operation and planning problems and are observed
to produce promising solutions to complex problem [27], [28],
