[30], [31]. Therefore, the proposed formulation is also solved
using traditional PSO and another advanced PSO variant
MPSPSO and a comparison of results obtained from PSO,
PSO-CF, MPSPSO is done.
The proposed formulation for optimal placement and sizing
of fast EV charging stations, while simultaneously satisfying
the objectives and constraints of the transportation network
and EPDN, is a multi-objective problem, which is discussed
in Section II. Section III presents the performance of proposed
formulation on a 30-node EPDN coupled with a 25-node
transportation network. Various cases, including varying initial
SOC of EVs and percentage growth of EVs per year, are also
analyzed to prove the proposed work’s efficacy and robustness.
The paper concludes in Section IV.
II. PROPOSED FORMULATION AND SOLUTION STRATEGY
The proposed multi-objective formulation for optimal plan-
ning and sizing of fast EV charging stations is discussed first,
followed by the solution methodology using PSO-CF.
A. Driving Range-Based Traffic Flow Capturing Model
The Driving range-based traffic Flow Capturing Model
(DFCM) proposes a strategy to locate charging stations that
maximises the number of EVs being charged from charging
stations in the transportation network while minimising the
queuing time. In this model, it is assumed that a EV departs
from origin (node α) with an initial battery capacity Es
o and
chooses the shortest route r to reach the destination (node ε).
The path r between nodes α and ε has transportation nodes β,
γ , and δ, as shown in Fig. 1. The EV wishes to depart node ε
with battery capacity Es
ε to cover a desired driving range ds
ε.
