IV. CONCLUSION
This paper performs the planning of fast EV charging
stations in a coupled transportation and EPDN to obtain their
optimal placement and sizing. The 25-node transportation
network is coupled with the 30-node EPDN on the basis of the
distance-based mapping. The DFCM is designed to maximize
the traffic flow coverage while reducing the queuing time
of EVs at the charging stations. The model aims to satisfy
the individual EV charging requirements along with the con-
straints of the transportation network. The EPDN objectives
of minimizing total active power loss, VDI, and the total
establishment cost of the charging stations are also considered,
while satisfying the bus voltage magnitude and power balance
constraints. The EV charging demand is determined by pre-
dicting the traffic volume with RF while considering weather
and time factors. A multi-objective problem is formulated by
considering the transportation network and EPDN’s objectives
and constraints simultaneously, which is solved and compared
using PSO-CF, PSO, and MPSPSO. The performance of
PSO-CF is observed to be better than the MPSPSO and PSO.
To the best of authors’ knowledge (also evidenced through
Table I), the proposed work is a first of its kind, and, hence,
numeric comparison with any previous work has not been
possible.
To illustrate the efficacy and robustness of the solution from
the proposed formulation, several cases of varying the initial
SOC of the EVs and varying the percentage growth of EVs
per year are analysed. In each case, the optimal placement
and sizing of fast charging stations in the coupled networks is
obtained while satisfying all of the constraints considered in
the analysis. However, the former case has a greater increase in
queuing time per EV, whereas the latter case has more increase
in the total establishment cost, power loss, VDI, as well as a
higher percentage of traffic coverage. It should also be noted
that Bus 26 of the EPDN is the most sensitive bus in both
cases. Furthermore, if the annual growth rate exceeds 20%, the
existing EPDN will need to be reinforced, and the associated
cost will be added separately to the total cost of the charging
stations. However, the uncertainties associated with EVs in the
planning strategy will also be considered in future.
