Abstract—The implementation of energy transformation 
strategies has led to tangible changes in the approaches to the 
organization 
of 
modern 
energy 
systems 
through 
the 
involvement of new generation sources and new types of 
consumers that require better planning and organization of 
distributed systems. One example of such innovations is the 
ubiquity of electric transportation in large cities, which is 
becoming widespread. This process is driven by various 
factors, the most important of which is the environmental 
safety factor of modern society.  Despite the fact that the 
development of technology makes such transport more and 
more capable and competitive with traditional types, there are 
some limitations, primarily due to the low autonomy of such 
vehicles, which leads to the need to organize specialized 
charging points. The problem of charging station location 
involves determining the most optimal locations for station 
placement, depending on the selected parameters of the target 
function, for which various approaches are used: linear 
programming, multi-criteria and meta-heuristic optimization, 
genetic and evolutionary algorithms. This paper considers the 
process of implementation of the software module for 
determining the optimal locations of electric vehicle charging 
stations based on the use of genetic algorithm, the main 
criterion of which is the maximum utilization rate of the 
operated stations. 
Keywords—genetic 
algorithms, 
optimization, 
electric 
transport, charging stations 
I. 
INTRODUCTION  
In recent years, electric vehicles have become widespread 
(Fig. 1), which is facilitated by the development of energy [1] 
storage technologies and the emergence of new designs of 
electric motors that make it possible to ensure high 
competitiveness of this type of vehicles [2]. 
 
Fig. 1. Global electric car stock country-wise, including both battery 
electric vehicles (BEVs) and plug-in hybrid electric vehicles (PHEVs) 
[3] 
Several major factors contribute to the active adoption of 
personal and public electric transportation: 
• 
Environmental friendliness. Electric cars do not 
produce greenhouse gases, which are one of the main 
causes of harmful effects on the climate [4], [5]; 
• 
High energy efficiency. Electric vehicles have higher 
efficiency than traditional internal combustion 
engines, allowing for more efficient use of energy 
and lower overall “fuel” costs and lower overall 
operating costs [6]; 
• 
Reduced dependence on hydrocarbon resources. A 
greater 
share 
of 
electric 
vehicles 
in 
total 
transportation reduces economic and geopolitical 
risks and increases energy security; 
Reduction of noise and vibrations. The use of electric 
vehicles allows to somewhat smooth out the general “sound 
background” [7], which is an important factor influencing 
human health.  
