At the same time, with the introduction and growth of 
electric vehicles, a number of challenges arise related to the 
creation and optimization of an appropriate energy 
infrastructure [8]: 
• 
organization of intelligent control systems for 
distributed energy infrastructure; 
• 
ensuring the sustainability of electricity supply; 
• 
organization of effective integration into the existing 
energy system. 
These tasks can be attributed to the second phase of 
efficient utilization of electric vehicles, while the first priority 
is to identify the proposed locations of charging stations to 
cover the existing demand. 
In this connection, the paper considers the process of 
implementation of the module of electric vehicle charging 
station placement based on the use of genetic algorithm, 
which takes into account two main factors of optimization of 
the final solution: the parameter of utilization of operating 
stations, and the use of priority points (parking zones) used 
as an initial set of potential coordinates for station placement. 
II. 
MATERIALS AND METHODS 
The problem of determining the proposed location of the 
charging station is a well-known problem, for the solution of 
which various approaches and methods of optimization are 
used, such as: genetic and evolutionary algorithms, neural 
networks [9], multi-criteria optimization methods [10], the 
classification of which is presented in Fig. 2. 
 
Fig. 2. Classification of optimization techniques 
After selecting the proposed optimization method, there 
is a task of forming input parameters, which are some spatial 
data, defining the constraint system and the key optimization 
parameter. There are two main approaches to solving such 
problems:  
• 
object-location 
configuration 
implies 
that 
optimization is performed on a certain set of 
predefined locations [11]; 
• 
A “site-to-site” formulation, implying that charging 
stations are freely available within a certain 
application area to cover existing needs [12]. 
The second approach is more complex, requiring more 
input parameters that cannot always be obtained from public 
data sources, so we will use the first formulation of the 
object-location optimization problem. 
Thus, it is necessary to define a preliminary set of 
assumed location coordinates, information about which can 
be obtained by using the OpenStreetMap tool [13]Error! 
Reference source not found.. The obtained set may be 
excessive, 
therefore, 
for 
efficient 
operation 
of 
the 
optimization algorithm, we obtain a part of the initial values 
using the values of the charging station coverage radius and 
the Haversine formula [14][13]. The general algorithm of the 
whole program is shown in Fig. 3. 
 
Fig. 3. General algorithm of the program 
III. 
PRACTICAL SIGNIFICANCE  
Since utilization rate is considered as the main efficiency 
criterion for the placement of charging stations, it is 
necessary to select a set of key locations to reach as many 
potential consumers as possible. One such site could be 
parking areas, which are likely to have additional space to 
accommodate charging infrastructure. The area of each 
facility was used as a weighting factor, resulting in areas with 
a larger area being prioritized. 
The city of Krasnodar was chosen as an example for the 
study, the map with the location of parking lots of which is 
shown in Figure 4a. Such a large number of parking lots can 
aggravate the use of the genetic algorithm, making its 
running time extremely long and the algorithm itself 
extremely demanding on resources [15]. To solve this 
problem, the most relevant parking zones with the largest 
area and with a predetermined radius of location were 
