125 
selected, for which a distance matrix was constructed by 
using the Haversine formula (Fig. 4b). 
    
 
 
                    a) 
  
 
 
b) 
Fig. 4. Visualization of parking spaces: a) all available parking areas; b) 
selection of the most suitable spaces (by area value) 
The obtained coordinates are the input parameters for the 
used genetic algorithm, the algorithm of which is presented 
in Fig. 5. 
 
Fig. 5. Block diagram of the genetic algorithm for determining optimal 
station locations 
After the first generation of formations is determined, the 
main cycle of the genetic algorithm is started, within which 
the parameters for each formation are calculated, the current 
best one is found, and all available formations are compared 
with it, which is necessary for realization of the procedure of 
softmax function calculation.  
The use of this algorithm allows to optimize the initial 
obtained station placement, taking into account the criterion 
of station utilization. Fig. 6 shows the result of using the 
optimization algorithm on the input set of proposed locations. 
 
Fig. 6. The result of the genetic algorithm 
IV. 
CONCLUSION 
The implemented station placement module can be used 
to determine the optimal placement of charging stations 
based on a set of starting points and a known estimated 
number of stations to be placed. The proposed approach is 
somewhat idealized as it does not fully take into account all 
parameters and factors that influence the success of a 
charging station. As a next step in development, additional 
data sets, such as road traffic and its importance, the number 
of residential buildings in the district, should be involved to 
allow a more realistic assessment of the available charging 
infrastructure needs. 
