Optimal Placement of Electric Vehicle Charging 
Station by Considering Dynamic Loads in Radial 
Distribution System 
Dandu Srinivas  
Research Scholar 
Department of Electrical Engineering 
JNTU Anantapur   
Anantapur, India 
srinivasphd226@gmail.com 
Dr.M. Ramasekhara Reddy 
Assistant Professor 
Department of Electrical Engineering 
JNTUA College of Engineering, Anantapur 
Anantapur, India 
ramasekharreddy.eee@jntua.ac.in 
Abstract— Electric vehicles with unique characteristics 
like lower noise, energy saving and pollution free due to 
reduction of carbon dioxide are consider to be the best 
choice for future automobile industry. The battery of 
electric vehicle (EV) must get recharged at charging 
stations when they are used for driving in urban area. 
Since 
electric 
charging 
stations 
will 
be 
used 
simultaneously by many EV. The existing distribution 
system might not be highly affected by the installation of 
charging stations if the numbers of electric vehicles are 
small. However, with the increase in the number of 
electric vehicles the characteristics of the electric vehicle 
charging patterns may have considerable impact on 
distribution systems which depends particularly on the 
electric vehicle charging location. There may be 
significant impacts like overloading and power losses in 
the system. These impacts could be mitigated by proper 
system planning and through strategic placement of 
Electric Vehicle Charging Station (EVCS) in the existing 
radial distribution network. In this research the optimal 
location EVCS are identified in radial distribution 
network and also the active power losses and system 
voltage profile are examined. This research proposes a 
heuristic algorithm called Particle Swarm Optimization 
(PSO) to optimize the IEEE 33 bus radial distribution 
system with electric vehicle charging stations. The prime 
objective is to place the EVCS at optimal location in 
existing radial distribution network by considering the 
real (active) power losses and also the voltage at the 
buses of the system. 
Keywords—Electric vehicle, Charging station, Radial 
distribution systems, Optimal placement, Particle swarm 
optimization 
I. INTRODUCTION 
Environmental issues have become one of the most 
serious concerns for the environmental researchers. Now 
one of the primary issues of big cities is growth in emission 
of greenhouse gas which is linked to use of internal 
combustion engines of fossil fuel cars. Greenhouse gases are 
being reduced through the use of various technologies. As 
an ecologically friendly transportation technology, Electric 
Vehicles (EVs) are giving tremendous potentials for 
increasing the power system dependability and flexibility. 
Among the many advantages of electric vehicles is a 
reduction in reliance on fossil fuels of 40-60 percent. Other 
advantages include convenience, safe charging, high 
performance, and flexibility in fuel choice.  
In the existing radial distribution systems, the current 
problems that are facing by EV’s and the obstacles for 
development of EV’s are the optimum placement of electric 
vehicle charging stations [1] and the charging time for a 
battery to get charged. It is fact that the power system 
operation and control has been already faced wide variety of 
problems due to rapid growth and integration of distributed 
generation but now if the integration of these large numbers 
of electric vehicle charging stations may become further 
burden for the power grid if not planned properly.  As the 
charging of maximum number of EV’s at same time will 
have the significant impact on electrical power grid because 
charging a greater number of EV’s at a time may lead to 
peak demand of electricity which can have significant 
impact on the electrical grid system. Therefore, necessary 
precautionary actions to be taken to avoid failure of 
electrical power grid system due to the peak demand. The 
placement of charging stations (CS’s) in this existing system 
with high energy demand can results in more power 
demand, this may cause disturbance in the distribution 
system. So, the analysis is required for optimal placement of 
CS’s by considering either by static size or dynamic size in 
the radial distribution system. The charging points in the 
charging station will charge the specified battery size of 
electric vehicle. The location of EVCS is the focus of 
current researchers. However, for the best EVCS placement 
the power losses and system voltage profile must be 
assessed. For lower bus systems, such as the 69 radial bus 
systems and the 119 radial bus system, etc., the method of 
trial and error for EVCS placement and sizing is very 
simple. The location of the charging station may be best 
served by looking for low sensitivity voltage buses. 
However, this way of searching is unable to deliver the best 
EVCS on greater bus radial systems. 
Heuristic algorithms were created as a result for the best 
placement of EVCS for EV as well as for reduced power 
losses [2] and subsequently to improve the system voltage 
profile. For the best position of the charging station, the 
researchers take into consideration restrictions like voltage 
and current limits. Since the EV's charging current is always 
real, the batteries power rating is expressed in kW. 
Therefore, in addition to the current load at the buses, extra 
real power loads must be provided in order to represent the 
EVCS connected in the radial bus system.  A heuristic 
approach called Particle Swarm Optimization (PSO) is 
proposed in this work for the best positioning of EVCS. The 
concept is used with the IEEE 33 bus radial distribution 
standard system while taking into account dynamic loads. 
