II. RELEVANT BACKGROUND 
Fig.1 shows the categorization of the effects of EV 
integration. The analysis of EV load impact is presented. The 
influence of EV load on distribution network [4] parameters 
comes first, then the effects on the environment and the 
economy. The potential benefits and drawbacks of 
integrating EV load into the distribution network are shown 
in Fig.1. 
 
Fig. 1 EV Load Impact Classification 
A. EV Load Affects on existing distribution system: 
The expansion of EVCS’s introduces various issues to 
existing distribution system. These topics have undergone 
careful evaluation recently. In the past researches it is seen 
that electric vehicle’s effect analysis is generally used to 
determine how inclusion of electric vehicle’s affect the 
electricity generation, the age of transformers, and the 
power efficiency of distribution systems. In fact, it's feasible 
that EV charging during times of high demand will increase 
that demand, necessitating an increase in generation 
capacity. Additionally, a higher demand for EVs will 
overload transformers in substations and services, reducing 
the lifespan of those components. Furthermore, EVCS’s can 
result in among other power quality problems [5] like 
current and voltage harmonics, voltage sags, and power 
fluctuations.  
 
 
 
1) Negative impacts: 
The first is the effect on the distribution system's power 
quality which is defined as the ability of power system 
which delivers continuous power to loads without any 
harmonics and a clean power supply. Two common power 
quality problems are harmonics and voltage sag/swelling in 
particular. Electric vehicle charging stations are creating 
those power quality problems when connecting to the power 
grid. As per IEEE 519 defining power quality, the (THD) 
total harmonic distortion values for power networks up to 69 
kV should be less than 5%. This study suggests that 
integration of EV’s to the grid and the EV load connection 
to existing distribution will results in increase in harmonic 
disturbances. The total harmonic distortion ranges at 4.82% 
for single EV which is connected to the device to 19.69% 
for about five EV’s using various modules. 
a) Voltage impact: Voltage impact: This section 
discusses how Plug in EV introduction influences voltage 
variations, which has an impact on how efficiently power is 
delivered to consumers. There is a voltage drop across the 
buses during charging due to adding of EV’s to the existing 
distribution network. The literature states that less than 95% 
of nominal voltage lost due to voltage loss in some 
locations. Due to that the system upgrades are necessary. 
With varying charging rates between 20 and 80 percent, the 
voltage deviates from the specified voltage by 12.7% to 
43.3% [4] penetration of PEV.  
b) power loss impact: Losses in the power system has 
become a significant problem during the energy demand that 
will be produced in the future is taken into account [12]. As 
stated by “reference” Dharmakeerthi. et. al 2011, for 62 
percent market penetration of PEVs, 40% of  loss in energy 
is seen during off-peak charging. The researchers found that 
when PEV adoption rose, network power losses increased 
considerably. Applying the ideal placement of the EVCS 
process would reduce the increase in power loss to a certain 
value.  
c) Reliability impact: In recent years, a difficult field 
of research has been the distribution network reliability 
studies. Specifically, statistical information on the failure 
rate, repair rate, average outage time, and the number of 
users is used to determine the distribution network's 
dependability 
indices 
[6]. 
Additionally 
to 
evaluate 
dependability and vulnerability of each bus in distribution 
network the term employed is bus reliability index. The 
stability analysis of the distribution system can be evaluated 
using reliability indices of the system. The system 
dependability indices are divided into customer and energy 
based categories. The official names of the customer based 
reliability indices are SAIFI, SAIDI, and CAIDI. While 
SAIDI specifies the average interruption time per customer 
served and SAIFI gives the information how many times 
that client encountered the power interruption in a specified 
time period. Additionally, SAIDI is influenced by the 
quantity of consumers as well as the length of the outage 
[7]. 
 
 
