Positive impacts: Advantage of the V2G programme 
is that The Vehicle to Grid scheme of EVCS’s has many 
benefits like lower cost EVCS operators, lower cost EVCS 
customers, and better EVCS load duration curves. In reality, 
the V2G program's primary advantage is the ability to 
transfer energy from automobile batteries to the grid during 
periods of high demand and to recharge the batteries during 
periods of low demand. According to the study's most 
encouraging finding, the system could handle wind 
integration of up to 59 percent of total grid generation 
capacity when EV participated in primary frequency 
regulation. However, a certain amount of solar energy can 
be used to charge an electric vehicle. 
The most encouraging finding of the study was that 59% 
of the grid's generating capacity could be supplied by wind 
energy when EVs were used for main frequency 
management. The EV, however, may be charged using a 
limited amount of solar power. 
III. PROBLEM FORMULATION 
With the rapid expansion of the electric vehicle industry 
wants an urgent need for charging stations, particularly in 
light of the relatively low energy storage capacity of EV 
batteries. Sixty-two percent of fleet cars will be replaced by 
EVs by 2050 if the current pace of adoption is maintained. 
Due to the rapidly expanding demand for electric vehicles 
(EVs), charging stations (CS) [12] are now a need. 
However, the research has not yet examined the need of 
studying how the introduction of EVCS would affect the 
already-in-place radial distribution system. With this study, 
we examine how the radial distribution system will change 
when EVCS is implemented. 
A. Distribution System Load Flow  
Due to several unique topological characteristics, load 
flow algorithms for power distribution systems are very 
different from those for transmission systems. Due to the 
radial nature and more R/X index of the branches a 
traditional load flow technique Newton-Raphson method not 
possible to apply. So for distribution systems a forward and 
backward sweep method is used. In this method with loads 
at each bus, the current from the last branch to the first 
branch may be determined. So, forward/backward load flow 
is the name given to this load flow [13].  
The fundamental power equation can be used to compute 
the bus currents [9]. 
