VI. CONCLUSION 
The usage of the EV’s will reduce the emission of 
greenhouse gas and will have many environmental benefits. 
The optimal placement of EVCS’s has become a high 
concern for the existing distribution network operator due to 
increase in EVCS’s installations. With the sudden increase of 
EV load penetration into the distribution system results in the 
mismatch of generation-load demand which in turn increases 
the losses in the system. This may lead to decline in the 
voltage stability margin due to decrease in voltage quality. 
Therefore, it is necessary to integrate the EVCS’s at suitable 
locations in order to reduce the harmful effects due to the 
penetration of EV load into the existing radial distribution 
system. This research proposes a new approach by 
considering dynamic loads to deal with the issues related to 
optimal placement of EVCS’s in the IEEE 33 bus radial 
distribution systems by using Particle Swarm Optimization 
(PSO). To determine the optimal location of EVCS’s the 
proposed PSO algorithm is applied on standard IEEE 33 bus 
radial distribution network with MATLAB environment. The 
performance of the proposed system is compared with and 
without charging station placement where the proposed PSO 
algorithm does not only helpful in finding the optimal 
location of EVCS but it also reduced the total computing 
time in finding the optimal EVCS locations. 
 Research Challenges and Future Research Directions: 
In this research the findings are that the active power 
losses are increased by adding EVCS to the existing IEEE 
33 bus radial distribution network as the current drawn from 
the substation is more which in turn increases the losses in 
the system. Therefore, there many attractive research 
directions to pursue in the future. One among them is to 
investigate the impacts of EVCS on the radial distribution 
system because it has been witnessed that the power losses 
were high in the system after the placement of the charging 
stations when compared with the power losses without 
charging stations. 
▪ 
The impact of rise in real power losses in the 
system can be mitigated by the reconfiguration 
of existing radial distribution network before 
finding the optimal location of EVCS. 
▪ 
The power losses in the system can be 
minimized if EVCS’s are placed far away from 
the substation along with the DG units.  
