Abstract—Electric Vehicles (EVs) are one of the most 
efficient technologies for the sustainable transport sector in the 
present world considering its almost nil carbon emission. To 
cope up with the ever-increasing demand of power for EV 
charging, the distribution system's power loss increases and 
significant changes in voltage profile occurs. Improper 
installation of the EV Charging Stations (EVCS) significantly 
reduces the power quality of the distribution network, 
impacting its efficient process. In this paper, the installation of 
EVCS in the IEEE 33 bus radial distribution system is being 
outlined. The distribution system has been split into three areas 
in order to reach charging facilities in various locations within 
an area and it has been ensured that one charging station is 
allocated in each area. The issue is being categorized as the 
optimization problem and it has been dealt using Symbiotic 
Organisms Search Algorithm (SOS) for finding the optimal 
location of EVCS. 
Keywords—Distribution System, Electric Vehicle (EVs), 
Electric Vehicle Charging Stations (EVCS), Real Power Loss 
Minimization, SOS. 
I. INTRODUCTION 
The most challenging concerns in the present generation 
are air pollution, global warming threat, and environmental 
issues [1]. Environmental awareness towards alarming 
emission of greenhouse gases, financial gains in terms of fuel 
use, and the incentives offered by the government are the key 
attributes for changing the mindset of people from 
conventional vehicles to EV [2]. The use of EVs is a technique 
to replace conventional fossil fuel-powered vehicles which 
helps to reduce carbon emissions and fossil fuel utilization [3]. 
For EV owners to charge their vehicles, EVCS is a basic 
necessity. The provision of charging infrastructure is 
inevitable for widespread EV implementation [4]. Thus, the 
proper allocation of EVCS is necessary for the distribution 
network by keeping the real power loss minimum with a 
proper voltage profile. The inappropriate positioning of EVCS 
will lead to additional energy consumption which creates a 
negative consequence on the power system network's energy 
requirements. 
The authors in [5] have used GWO and WOA optimization 
tools to solve EVCS allocation issues in IEEE 33 bus 
distribution network. In [6], the authors have implemented 
parking lot allotment using GA in the distribution network. 
The authors in [7] have assigned the charging station in a 
distribution network that overlaps with a traffic network in 
order to reduce power loss and voltage fluctuation. In [8]-[10], 
most of the research works focus on the power loss 
minimization for optimally allocating EVCS using different 
soft computing techniques. 
The proposed research emphasizes on optimally allocating 
EVCS in IEEE 33 bus radial distribution system. The 
distribution network is separated into three areas for 
widespread access to EVCS. V2G is an exceptional attribute 
that improves power system quality. Both G2V and V2G 
provisions have been considered. In this research paper, the 
SOS algorithm has been implemented for allocating EVCS at 
suitable positions where the distribution network's active 
power loss is minimized along with maintaining a healthy 
voltage profile. 
The research paper is arranged as follows: Section II deals 
with problem optimization where the real power loss 
minimization is the objective function along with constraints. 
Section III includes the SOS optimization tool applied to the 
system which includes a comprehensive assessment of the 
system considering various scenarios for optimally allocating 
the best position for EVCS. Section IV deals with results 
obtained from the cases considered to examine the impacts on 
power system parameters. Section V depicts the concluding 
remarks of this research paper. 
II. PROBLEM OPTIMIZATION 
