IV. RESULTS AND ANALYSIS 
The real power loss as well as other parameters of power 
system of the distribution network has been calculated using 
backward forward sweep load flow. We have considered 
charging rate as 19 kW [2] in G2V configuration and 
discharging rate as 8 kW [13] in V2G configuration. The 
authors have assumed that 20% EV can be operated in V2G 
configuration. We have illustrated two scenarios in this paper. 
Firstly, we have allocated the EVCS without separating the 
distribution network into different areas. Secondly, we have 
allocated the EVCS into three different areas after dividing the 
distribution network. For an instant of time, the problem has 
been solved. At the charging point, four instances have been 
taken into account: 10, 20, 30, and 40 EVs are linked at that 
point of time. A bad case scenario has been considered in 
which the number of arrived EVs in the system cannot exceed 
40 at a particular time. The EVCS has been allocated based on 
these scenarios. 
According to IEEE 33 bus radial distribution network, the 
nominal loads have been connected at different nodes. The 
extra load due to EV charging has been taken into account at 
that node where the EVCS is assigned. The number of EVs 
along with charging rate and discharging rate determines the 
load to be connected in V2G and G2V configurations. 
To perform this research, the MATLAB R2018b 
programming language is being chosen, installed on a 
system having an Intel i5 processor, having clock speed of 
2.40 GHz, and RAM of 8 GB. 
